],"variants":[{"name":"Agricola","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Algert, Cornelis.  German Aloys, Otto.","German and Dutch: humanistic surname, a translation into Latin of German   Bauer   and Dutch   Boer   ‘farmer’."]},{"name":"Bauerlein","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Gunther.","German (<b>Bäuerlein</b>): standardized diminutive of   Bauer  , originally occurring in southern dialects as <b>Bäuerle</b> (see   Bauerle  ),   Beuerle  , and   Beyerle  ."]},{"name":"Baur","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Uli, Ulrich, Alfons, Arno, Erwin, Friedrich, Fritz, Urs, Wilhelm, Wolfgang.","South German: variant of   Bauer   ‘peasant’ or ‘neighbor, fellow citizen’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine)."]},{"name":"Ankenbauer","meanings":["South German (mainly Bavaria): from Middle High German <i>anken</i> ‘butter’ + <i>būr</i> ‘farmer’ (see   Bauer  ), hence an occupational name for a dairy farmer. Alternatively, the first element may be a topographic term, <i>Anke</i>, meaning ‘slight rise in the ground’, or an old term <i>ank</i> ‘watery’, hence ‘farmer with fields in a wet area’."]},{"name":"Bierle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto.","South German: from a diminutive of   Bauer  , an unrounded form of Alemannic <b>Bürle</b> (compare   Buehrle  )."]},{"name":"Beurer","meanings":["(2010: NA)","South German: habitational name for someone from any of various places called Beuren, from Old High German <i>būr</i> ‘small dwelling’ (see   Bauer  )."]},{"name":"Bauerle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernhard, Albrecht, Helmut, Horst, Lothar, Merwin, Otto.","South German (<b>Bäuerle</b>): from a Swabian diminutive of   Bauer  ."]},{"name":"Bauers","meanings":["German: variant of   Bauer  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, or from a first part of an original compound name (e.g.   Bauersfeld  )."]},{"name":"Beuerle","meanings":["South German: diminutive of   Bauer  ."]},{"name":"Baumann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Otto, Gerhard, Ernst, Heinz, Guenter, Armin, Dieter, Erna, Friedrich.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): status name for a peasant or a nickname meaning ‘neighbor, fellow citizen’, from Middle High German <i>būman</i>, German <i>Baumann</i> ‘peasant’ (see   Bauer  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), the Netherlands, Denmark, Poland, and some other European countries. Compare   Bauman   and   Bowman  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Bauer was born in 1419, in Germany. She had at least 1 daughter with Bauer."},"et":{"1419–":"1419–Surnud","1419–1490":"1419–1490","1465–1505":"1465–1505","1419–Female":"1419–Surnud","1465":"1465","1419":"1419","1490":"1490","1505":"1505","Germany":"Saksamaa","Neundorf, Annaberg, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Neundorf, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1419–":"1419–Kuollut","1419–1490":"1419–1490","1465–1505":"1465–1505","1419–Female":"1419–Kuollut","1465":"1465","1419":"1419","1490":"1490","1505":"1505","Germany":"Saksa","Neundorf, Annaberg, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Neundorf, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Saksa"},"fr":{"1419–":"1419–Décédée","1419–1490":"1419–1490","1465–1505":"1465–1505","1419–Female":"1419–Décédée","1465":"1465","1419":"1419","1490":"1490","1505":"1505","Germany":"Allemagne","Neundorf, Annaberg, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Neundorf, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Allemagne","lifeSummary":"Bauer est née en 1419, à Allemagne. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Bauer."},"de":{"1419–":"1419–Verstorben","1419–1490":"1419–1490","1465–1505":"1465–1505","1419–Female":"1419–Verstorben","1465":"1465","1419":"1419","1490":"1490","1505":"1505","Germany":"Deutschland","Neundorf, Annaberg, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Neundorf, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Deutschland","lifeSummary":"Bauer wurde 1419 in Deutschland geboren. Sie hatte mit Bauer mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"1419–":"1419–Desede","1419–14